commText: Jaiswal and Tanush Kotian are at the crease. Jaiswal is on strike. Arshdeep Singh will open the attack
Arshdeep Singh to Jaiswal, 3 runs, back of a length ball outside off, swinging away, Jaiswal chops it towards covers where Brar dives but can't stop it. Third man gets around to cut it off
Arshdeep Singh to Tanush Kotian, no run, back of a length ball angling across Tanush Kotian. He taps it with an open bat face towards backward point
Arshdeep Singh to Tanush Kotian, wide, a good amount of inswing on this length ball but Arshdeep Singh can't quite control it as he sprays it down leg. Wided
Arshdeep Singh to Tanush Kotian, no run, pitched up ball swinging in on off, Tanush Kotian leans ahead and drives it on the up to mid-off
Arshdeep Singh to Tanush Kotian, no run, a pitched up ball on off, hint of inswing, Tanush Kotian leans ahead carefully and blocks it towards mid-off

Arshdeep Singh to Tanush Kotian, FOUR, nicely played! First runs in IPL for Tanush Kotian! Shortish delivery shaping across Tanush Kotian. He rises with the bounce and cuts it past backward point to find the fence
Arshdeep Singh to Tanush Kotian, 1 run, short of length ball shaping away from off, Tanush Kotian punches it to sweeper cover to retain strike
Kagiso Rabada, right-arm fast, comes into the attack
Rabada to Tanush Kotian, no run, a fuller length ball swinging in on off at 138.4kph, Tanush Kotian checks his drive and it goes on the bounce to mid-off
A slip in place for Rabada as well
Rabada to Tanush Kotian, no run, good length ball in the channel, a tentative punch from Tanush Kotian from the crease and he gets it off the inner half towards mid-on
Rabada to Tanush Kotian, no run, pitched up ball outside off, Tanush Kotian leans ahead and mistimes his drive to cover-point. Three dots in a row

Rabada to Tanush Kotian, 1 run, a direct-hit would have been very close! A length ball angling in, punched on the up to the left of Curran at mid-off and the batters took off. He misses his shy. The replay shows that Tanush Kotian would have been just in
Rabada to Jaiswal, FOUR, beautiful timing! Pitched up ball on middle and off, Jaiswal flicks it nonchalantly through mid-wicket to get the desired result. All grace and timing there
Rabada to Jaiswal, no run, beaten! Fuller length ball shaping across Jaiswal. He tries to drive it on the up through covers but is beaten for pace and a bit of extra bounce
Sam Curran, left-arm fast medium, comes into the attack
Sam Curran to Tanush Kotian, no run, length ball swinging into middle and leg and cramping Tanush Kotian for room. He can only push it back to Sam Curran. He mimics a throw back towards the stumps

Sam Curran to Tanush Kotian, no run, an off-cutter on a length, grips and cuts across Tanush Kotian to open him up in his stance. He pushes at it and gets an outside edge that drops well short of the keeper to his right
Sam Curran to Tanush Kotian, 1 run, a length ball on middle and leg, holds up on the surface again, a tentative push from Tanush Kotian and it's just away from Sam Curran's reach to his right
Sam Curran to Jaiswal, no run, fuller length ball on off, Jaiswal eases it towards mid-on
Sam Curran to Jaiswal, no run, another cutter into the surface, Jaiswal makes room but can only punch it to covers. Smart bowling from Sam Curran
Sam Curran to Jaiswal, 1 run, another slower back of a length ball outside off, Jaiswal cuts it hard but finds Brar at cover-point who dives to his right to make a half-stop but a single results
Arshdeep Singh [1.0-0-9-0] is back into the attack
Arshdeep Singh to Jaiswal, FOUR, lovely! Slower ball at 115.5 clicks outside off, Jaiswal reads it perfectly as he leans ahead and drills the drive past extra cover for a rocketing boundary
Arshdeep Singh to Jaiswal, 2 runs, pace on this time on a back of a length on off at 135.3 clicks, Jaiswal works it to the left of deep backward square leg and comes back for the second run
Arshdeep Singh to Jaiswal, 1 run, back of a length ball shaping in on off, Jaiswal swipes it straight towards deep square leg. Didn't hit it well
Arshdeep Singh to Tanush Kotian, 1 run, a length ball outside off, Tanush Kotian punches it on the up. Livingstone at extra cover misfields and concedes a single
Jaiswal bails out as Arshdeep Singh was about to deliver the ball. The spider cam was the reason for him getting distracted
Arshdeep Singh to Jaiswal, 1 run, another slower shortish ball down leg, Jaiswal mistimes the pull towards short fine leg for a brisk single

Arshdeep Singh to Tanush Kotian, FOUR, perhaps this is the shot that will get Tanush Kotian going! A shortish ball that sits up nicely for Tanush Kotian. He stands tall and pulls it over the wide mid-on area for a boundary. 13 runs off the over

Sam Curran to Jaiswal, FOUR, if you feed Jaiswal outside off, he will more often than not get you away! On a back of a length outside off, Jaiswal throws his bat at it and cuts it in the gap between backward point and short third to get the desired result
Sam Curran to Jaiswal, 1 run, fuller length ball angling in on middle and off, Jaiswal pushes it off the inner half towards deep mid-wicket
Sam Curran to Tanush Kotian, no run, a play and a miss! 132.5kph length ball just outside off, Tanush Kotian goes at it with hard hands but only meets thin air
Sam Curran to Tanush Kotian, no run, a back of a length ball around off at 125.8kph, Tanush Kotian looks to punch it through covers but misses again
Sam Curran to Tanush Kotian, 1 run, 113.3kph slower fuller length ball on the pads, worked towards mid-wicket to rotate strike
Sam Curran to Jaiswal, wide, a pacy short ball but it's too high, Jaiswal was shaping for the pull but bails out. Wided for height

Sam Curran to Jaiswal, no run, another off-pace ball on a back of a length on off, Jaiswal waits for it and punches it straight to extra cover. Good comeback by Sam Curran after being hit for a boundary first ball
Over Summary (1-5 ov) * Tanush Kotian gets going with a well placed boundary * Jaiswal too gets going with a lovely whip off Rabada * Arshdeep Singh concedes 13 runs in the 4th over
Kagiso Rabada [1.0-0-5-0] is back into the attack

Rabada to Tanush Kotian, FOUR, that's an audacious shot! A length ball angling in on middle, Tanush Kotian clears his front leg and smashes it past the right side of mid-on for a boundary. He is growing in confidence slowly but certainly
Rabada to Tanush Kotian, no run, back of a length ball on off, Tanush Kotian's feet go nowehere this time as he pushes at it and gets an inside edge onto the pads
Sweeper cover comes inside the ring and mid-wicket goes back
Rabada to Tanush Kotian, 1 run, back of a length ball shaping in on middle and leg, tucked to mid-wicket for an easy single
Rabada to Jaiswal, no run, good bounce and carry! This one takes off from a fuller length, Jaiswal tries to drive it with the angle through covers but misses
Rabada to Jaiswal, 2 runs, fullish ball outside off, Jaiswal opens his bat-face and places it past the left side of short third. The fielder in the deep gets across to his right to cut it off
Rabada to Jaiswal, no run, a pacy back of a length ball shaping across Jaiswal at 144.6 clicks. He has an unnecessary poke and is lucky not to nick it behind
This is the first time that RR haven't lost a wicket inside the Powerplay this season!
Liam Livingstone, right-arm leg break, comes into the attack
Livingstone to Tanush Kotian, no run, 94.4kph, flat leggie just outside off, cut straight to backward point off the back foot
Livingstone to Tanush Kotian, no run, 100.3kph, another away-turner, Tanush Kotian fails to make contact with his cut shot
Livingstone to Tanush Kotian, no run, 88.2kph, spinning away from a length, pushed to extra cover
Livingstone to Tanush Kotian, no run, 95.9kph, fuller leggie, Tanush Kotian gets low to sweep hard and doesn't connect
Livingstone to Tanush Kotian, 1 run, 94.7kph, slaps the cut to sweeper cover
Round the wicket to Jaiswal
Livingstone to Jaiswal, wide, 93.9kph, legbreak spinning down leg, past Jaiswal's flick

Livingstone to Jaiswal, FOUR, full leggie, clipped with the spin through midwicket. A slight miscommunication between the batters as Jaiswal wants the second but his partner doesn't. However, they are helped by the Punjab fielders. Deep midwicket and long-on converge and the former misfields to let the ball hit the rope
Lowest run-rates in the Powerplay in 2024 7.52 - RR 7.77 - PBKS 8.11 - GT 8.27 - RCB
Harshal Patel, right-arm fast medium, comes into the attack

Harshal Patel to Tanush Kotian, 1 run, 133.8kph, pitched up, driven to mid-off for a sharp single. Curran doesn't hit the target at the bowler's end and Kotian makes his ground with a dive. Fifty up for RR!
Harshal Patel to Jaiswal, 1 run, short ball that comes slower than Jaiswal expects it to. Miscues the pull towards short fine leg off the inner edge

Harshal Patel to Tanush Kotian, 1 run, 137.1kph, short of a good length, Tanush Kotian stands tall and smashes it back to the bowler who can't react in time. The ball hits the bowler's fingers and rolls towards mid-on. Very tough chance!
Harshal Patel to Jaiswal, 1 run, 136.9kph, back of a length, tucked through midwicket
Harshal Patel to Tanush Kotian, 2 runs, 139.6kph, quick hands from Tanush Kotian as he fiercely cuts this length ball outside off. Rabada runs to his left from deep point and slides to stop it
Harshal Patel to Tanush Kotian, 1 run, 122.1kph, slower and fuller, driven down the pitch and Harshal Patel half-stops it with his right hand in his followthrough
Livingstone to Tanush Kotian, no run, 87.6kph, full delivery, Kotian clears his front leg to slog across the line and inside-edges it onto his pad
Livingstone to Tanush Kotian, THATS OUT!! Bowled!!

Livingstone to Tanush Kotian, out Bowled!! Gone! This was on the cards. Plenty of dot balls, he tries to slog his way out of trouble and perishes in the process. Pushed quicker and flatter by Livingstone, Kotian shimmies down the track to swing it over midwicket. Got saved by an inside edge last ball but this time he misses it altogether to hear the death rattle. Tanush Kotian b Livingstone 24(31) [4s-3]
Strategic timeout! Kotian hit three boundaries but he's taken 31 balls for his 24. However, the asking rate is still under 8 RPO. Let's see if Punjab can exert more pressure.
Sanju Samson, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Livingstone to Samson, no run, 87.8kph, with a slip in place, Livingstone bowls a very full delivery outside off, pushed to backward point
Livingstone to Samson, no run, 98.3kph, legbreak outside off, Samson cuts off the back foot but can't get it past short third man
Livingstone to Samson, 1 run, 95.2kph, stays back and drives this away-turner to long-off to get off the mark
Livingstone to Jaiswal, 1 run, 91.4kph, turns into an offie now Livingstone as he bowls an in-drifter, push-driven to long-on
Spin from both ends now!
Harpreet Brar, Left arm orthodox, comes into the attack
Harpreet Brar to Jaiswal, 1 run, 99.8kph, round the wicket, flat and quick on leg, flicked to deep midwicket
Stays round the wicket against Samson. A slip in place as well
Harpreet Brar to Samson, 1 run, in-dart, pulled through midwicket for a single
Harpreet Brar to Jaiswal, 2 runs, 90.9kph, fuller and wider, Jaiswal reaches out to cut it to deep point

Harpreet Brar to Jaiswal, 2 runs, 103.1kph, Brar attacks the sticks, Jaiswal turns it gently in front of square on the leg-side and calls his partner for the second. The throw comes to the keeper's end and Jaiswal is comfortably in
Harpreet Brar to Jaiswal, 1 run, 90.8kph, Brar pulls his length back by a fraction and that's been worked into the midwicket pocket for a single

Lowest strike-rate in an IPL innings for RR 66.66 - 22(33) - Steven Smith vs SRH, Ahmedabad, 2014 76.47 - 26*(34) - Steven Smith vs CSK, Abu Dhabi, 2020 77.41 - 24(31) - Tanush Kotian vs PBKS, Mullanpur, 2024 78.12 - 25(32) - Rahul Dravid vs RCB, Bengaluru, 2012 79.54 - 35*(44) - Graeme Smith vs CSK, Jaipur, 2008 *minimum 30 balls faced
Harpreet Brar to Samson, 1 run, 95.2kph, cut with the spin to deep cover

Over Summary (6-10 ov) * Rajasthan Royals reach 43 for 0 at the end of the batting PP * Both batters continued to find the boundaries at regular intervals * Livingstone breaks the 56-run opening stand, cleans up Kotian for 24 * The Royals reach 66 for 1 at the halfway stage of the chase.
Livingstone to Samson, SIX, 88.7kph, full and in the slot, Samson clears his front leg, gets under it and thumps this leggie downtown. Struck hard and over the bowler's head
Livingstone to Samson, 1 run, 99.3kph, slightly shorter, hurriedly pulled to long-on
Livingstone to Jaiswal, 1 run, 91.5kph, angled in from round the wicket and Jaiswal clips it in front of square on the leg-side
Livingstone to Samson, FOUR, 94.3kph, Livingstone bowls short and Samson is quick to trek back and pull it. Superb placement as he splits the gap between deep midwicket and long-on

Livingstone to Samson, no run, 91.5ph, slapped back towards the bowler, Livingstone leans to his right in his followthrough and the ball hits the sticks at the bowler's end. An appeal for run-out and it's been sent upstairs. "No contact with the bowler's hand," says the TV umpire. Even Livingstone felt the same
Livingstone completes his bowling action but doesn't deliver the ball...
Livingstone to Samson, 1 run, 87.9kph, puched with the spin to deep point. 13 runs off the over!
Equation: 69 runs | 54 balls.
Kagiso Rabada [2.0-0-12-0] is back into the attack
Rabada to Samson, 1 run, 135.3kph, short of length ball on leg, glanced away to deep square leg
Rabada to Jaiswal, no run, 139.6kph, fuller length delivery, drilled straight to mid-off
Rabada switches to round the wicket
Rabada to Jaiswal, 2 runs, the change almost works! 142.5kph, in-slanter, not much room to be cutting and Jaiswal gets an inside edge that eludes the sticks and rolls to fine leg
Rabada to Jaiswal, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Rabada to Jaiswal, out Caught by Harshal Patel!! Rabada comes back to remove Jaiswal. Banged in short outside off, Jaiswal clears his front leg and goes after it. Flashes his bat hard for an upper-cut but gets it off the bottom part of the bat. Ends up hitting it straight down third man's throat. Jaiswal falls after getting a start. Jaiswal c Harshal Patel b Rabada 39(28) [4s-4]
Riyan Parag, right handed bat, comes to the crease

Rabada to Riyan Parag, no run, 145.9kph, lbw appeal, turned down and Punjab review it. A pacy yorker first up and Parag probably got some wood on it. Yes. Big inside edge! "Clear deflection," says the TV umpire and he doesn't even need UltraEdge. Punjab burn a review!

Rabada to Riyan Parag, 1 run, 140.9kph, nips back in from a short of length, Riyan Parag defends from the crease and gets an inside edge onto his thigh pad. The ball dies down on the leg-side and Samson calls his partner for a quick single. Parag is late to take off but he's safe
Here's Brar against two right-handers
Harpreet Brar [1.0-0-8-0] is back into the attack
Harpreet Brar to Riyan Parag, no run, 96.3kph, fullish ball on the stumps, Parag defends
Harpreet Brar to Riyan Parag, 1 run, 94kph, middle-stump line, worked through midwicket
Harpreet Brar to Samson, 1 run, 98.2kph, in-dart around off, punched to the left of cover who makes a diving stop
Harpreet Brar to Riyan Parag, 1 run, 97.3kph, non-turner, flicked to deep midwicket off the back foot
Harpreet Brar to Samson, 1 run, stays back to a full delivery and drives hard to sweeper cover
Harpreet Brar to Riyan Parag, 1 run, 89.7kph, full and just outside off, driven along the ground to long-off
Equation: 60 runs | 42 balls. Rabada to bowl his final over...
Rabada to Riyan Parag, 1 run, 139.5kph, short of length outside off, steered to third man
Rabada to Samson, THATS OUT!! Lbw!!

Rabada to Samson, out Lbw!! 134.3kph, vociferous appeal for lbw and up goes Anil Kumar Chaudhary's finger. Samson reluctantly reviews. Lack of bounce from a back of a length, Samson shapes to pull and misses as the ball scoots under his blade. Struck on the back thigh adjacent to the sticks and that's hitting middle! RR lose their captain as well as a review. Big wicket for Punjab who continue to fight. Replays show that it was a leg-cutter from Rabada which wasn't picked by the batter. Samson lbw b Rabada 18(14) [4s-1 6s-1]
Dhruv Jurel, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Rabada to Dhruv Jurel, no run, pacy bouncer, Dhruv Jurel ducks under it
Rabada to Dhruv Jurel, no run, 138.4kph, short of length ball, tapped into the off-side

Rabada to Dhruv Jurel, 1 run, 139kph, beautiful delivery! Rabada squares up the batter as this length ball straightens off the deck. Dhruv Jurel turns into an I0$ as he pokes and the outside edge takes the ball to third man

Rabada to Riyan Parag, no run, short of a good length ball just outside off, Riyan Parag watchfully fences it to backward point. Superb stuff from Rabada. He's removed Jaiswal and Samson in this spell and finishes with 4-0-18-2

Strategic timeout! The asking rate is approaching 10 RPO but RR have their in-form batter - Riyan Parag - out in the middle. A couple of big-hitters to follow as well. Punjab's bowlers have been very good so far, they haven't allowed the batters to dictate terms. Equation: 58 runs | 36 balls.
Harpreet Brar to Dhruv Jurel, no run, 100.5kph, in-dart on off, knocked back to the bowler
Harpreet Brar to Dhruv Jurel, 1 run, 86.4kph, slower and drifting into middle and leg, worked through midwicket
Harpreet Brar to Riyan Parag, FOUR, in the air and safe! 96.2kph, fullish ball outside off and Riyan Parag throws his arms at it to flay it over the leaping backward point fielder
Harpreet Brar to Riyan Parag, 1 run, 99.1kph, fuller ball, clipped to deep midwicket
Harpreet Brar to Dhruv Jurel, 1 run, 95.1kph, pulled to deep midwicket
Rabada vs RR Matches: 8 Wickets: 14 Avg: 18.85 SR: 13.5 ER: 8.33 BBI: 3/35
Harpreet Brar to Riyan Parag, 2 runs, 95.9kph, width on offer, Riyan Parag slaps the cut to the right of deep cover who sprints across and mops it up
Equation: 49 runs | 30 balls.
Sam Curran [2.0-0-9-0] is back into the attack

Over Summary (11-15 ov) * Livingstone concedes 13 runs in the 11th over of the innings * Jaiswal holes out to third man off Rabada for 39 * Riyan Parag survives a first-ball review for LBW * Samson trapped LBW by Rabada, OUT for 18 * Rabada finishes with excellent figures of 2 for 18
Sam Curran to Dhruv Jurel, 1 run, 125.8kph, fuller than a length, driven to the right of mid-off
Sam Curran to Riyan Parag, 1 run, 128.7kph, back of a length, nudged towards midwicket and Parag eyes a second. Gets rightly sent back as Curran is quick to get to the ball

Sam Curran to Dhruv Jurel, 1 run, 130.8kph, short of a good length, dabbed straight to short third man and the batters set off for a risky single. However, Harshal Patel misfields. Curran has his hands on head

Sam Curran to Riyan Parag, 1 run, dropped! 116.3kph, slower delivery, cutter, Riyan Parag miscues the heave to long-on. Livingstone comes in from long-on and is a bit lethargic as he dives forward. Goes with both hands but fails to hold onto it. How costly will it be?
Sam Curran to Dhruv Jurel, 1 run, 116.5kph, pace off again, Dhruv Jurel pushes hard and inside-edges to deep square leg

Sam Curran to Riyan Parag, 1 run, 115.7kph, was that a chance? Slower ball again, Parag is early to close his bat-face and gets a leading edge that goes over the bowler's head. Curran looks to take an overhead catch in his followthrough but the ball was probably too high for him
Equation: 43 runs | 24 balls.
Arshdeep Singh [2.0-0-22-0] is back into the attack
Arshdeep Singh to Riyan Parag, no run, back of a length, Parag shapes to pull and misses

Arshdeep Singh to Riyan Parag, SIX, 131kph, streaky and much-needed for RR! Shortish ball, Parag swings hard to pull over midwicket and gets a fat top edge that flies over the keeper's head. Goes all the way

Arshdeep Singh to Riyan Parag, 2 runs, 135.3kph, length ball outside off, Riyan Parag wafts his bat at it and gets an inside edge that eludes the leg-stump before rolling to fine leg. Bhatia runs back and does well to stop the ball from hitting the fence
Arshdeep Singh to Riyan Parag, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Arshdeep Singh to Riyan Parag, out Caught by Rabada!! The slower ball does the trick! 120.5kph, pace off and into the wicket, Riyan Parag spots the length but is a bit early into his pull shot. Top-edges, more height than distance. Rabada, at deep midwicket, calls for it, settles under it and takes a calm catch. The in-form Parag departs for 23, wasn't at his fluent best today. Riyan Parag c Rabada b Arshdeep Singh 23(18) [4s-1 6s-1]
Shimron Hetmyer, left handed bat, comes to the crease
Arshdeep Singh to Hetmyer, 1 run, 138kph, length ball on middle and leg, clipped towards midwicket and Hetmyer gets off the mark with a single
DRS!

Arshdeep Singh to Dhruv Jurel, no run, another wicket? Umpire Tapan Sharma took his time to raise his finger but Dhruv Jurel has reviewed. Back of a length ball that goes away with the angle, Jurel looks to turn it into the leg-side and the ball seems to have missed the outside edge. The TV umpire is convinced that there's no outside edge and doesn't use UltraEdge. He asks for ball-tracking and it's pitched outside leg! Jurel survives and it's a successful review
Harshal Patel [1.0-0-7-0] is back into the attack
Harshal Patel to Hetmyer, 1 run, 136.7kph, full delivery outside off, Hetmyer leans across and drives to the right of extra cover
Harshal Patel to Dhruv Jurel, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Harshal Patel to Dhruv Jurel, out Caught by Shashank Singh!! Shashank Singh takes a good catch! 133.9kph, Dhruv Jurel walks across to heave this short of a good length ball over the leg-side. Hits him high on the bat and Shashank runs in from deep midwicket and slides to gobble it up. Dhruv Jurel c Shashank Singh b Harshal Patel 6(11)
Equation: 33 runs | 16 balls. Two WI batters out in the middle, but stroke-making hasn't been easy today...
Rovman Powell, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Harshal Patel to Powell, 2 runs, 137.3kph, fuller than a length outside off, Powell drives to backward point
Harshal Patel to Powell, 1 run, 136.6kph, in-angling fullish ball, Powell bunts it through midwicket for a single
Harshal Patel to Hetmyer, FOUR, 133.9kph, shortish delivery, Hetmyer clears his front leg to heave it away between deep midwicket and long-on. Hits him high on the bat but he's muscled it
Harshal Patel to Hetmyer, SIX, 134.3kph, bad ball and punished. Short and down leg, Hetmyer swivels and helps it on its way. Pulled over fine leg for a maximum. 14 runs off the over!
Equation: 20 runs | 12 balls. Curran to bowl th penultimate over.
Sam Curran [3.0-0-15-0] is back into the attack

Sam Curran to Powell, FOUR, hammered! 121.6kph, off-speed full delivery outside off, Powell walks across, bends his back leg and drills it past mid-off. Bairstow, the man in the deep, sprints and drives but to no avail
Sam Curran to Powell, FOUR, 130,1kph, very full outside off and Powell leans across to slap-drive it through extra cover. Back-to-back boundaries!
Sam Curran to Powell, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Sam Curran to Powell, out Caught by Jitesh Sharma!! Edged and gone! Powell is walking. Banged in short outside off, Powell probably didn't expect it. Good lift outside off and Powell looks to pull through backward square leg. Not a convincing shot and all he manages to get is a faint top edge. Jitesh Sharma doesn't err. Punjab continue to fight. Powell c Jitesh Sharma b Sam Curran 11(5) [4s-2]
Keshav Maharaj, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Sam Curran to Maharaj, 1 run, 130.3kph, away-angler, dabbed to third man
Livingstone and Curran having a discussion. What's Hetmyer thinking?
Sam Curran to Hetmyer, 1 run, 131.9kph, full delivery angled in and Hetmyer is happy to take a single. Flicked through midwicket
This should be a free-hit for Maharaj. He should swing hard. Mid-off, third man and fine leg inside the circle
Sam Curran to Maharaj, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Sam Curran to Maharaj, out Caught by Livingstone!! Holes out! 125.4kph, full and in the slot, Maharaj clears his front leg to go over long-on. The bat turns and hence the timing goes awry. Hits it straight to Livingstone who doesn't err on this occasion. Excellent comeback from Curran after conceding a couple of boundaries in this over. Maharaj c Livingstone b Sam Curran 1(2)
Equation: 10 runs | 6 balls. Arshdeep to bowl it. He's up against Hetmyer. Not much batting to follow...
Trent Boult, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Arshdeep Singh [3.0-0-31-1] is back into the attack
Arshdeep Singh to Hetmyer, no run, DOT! 136.6kph, yorker outside off, Hetmyer walks across and swings hard but doesn't lay bat on ball
10 runs | 5 balls.

Arshdeep Singh to Hetmyer, no run, 135.9kph, another yorker, Hetmyer gets low to go over midwicket/mid-on, gets an inside edge onto his body and the ball rolls towards the off-side. Hetmyer doesn't take the single., Big roar from the crowd
10 runs | 4 balls.

Arshdeep Singh to Hetmyer, SIX, 138kph, wow! That's a superb hit from Hetmyer. He shimmies down the track and it's not a yorker from Arshdeep. Turns it into a half-volley and smashes it over straight long-on for a flat six
4 runs | 3 balls.
Arshdeep Singh to Hetmyer, 2 runs, 140.7kph, shortened length, pulled to the left of long-on. Curran gets to the ball quickly but he fails to collect it cleanly. Easy two
2 runs | 2 balls.

Arshdeep Singh to Hetmyer, SIX, hit-me ball and Hetmyer accepts it gleefully! 137.8kph, high full toss down leg and Hetmyer swings it over fine leg. Hits the boundary cushion on the full and RR win by 3 wickets!

23:13 Local Time, 17:43 GMT, 23:13 IST: Another close encounter between these two teams! After the first innings, Rajasthan Royals were firm favourites but Punjab fought hard. Inserted to bat, Punjab hardly found any momentum with the bat. Ashutosh Sharma came in as the Impact Player at number eight and top-scored with a 16-ball 31 to take his team's total close to 150 on a sluggish track. In reply, Rajasthan didn't lose a single wicket in the powerplay but they managed to score just 38 runs in that phase. Kotian, batting at the top, struggled and fell in the ninth over. The asking rate was under check but Rabada picked two crucial wickets (Jaiswal and Samson) in two overs. The Punjab bowlers fought valiantly to put the RR batters under pressure. When Jurel holed out to deep midwicket, RR needed 33 runs in 16 balls and that's when the two Caribbean big-hitters joined hands. They scored 18 runs in 4 balls but Curran nipped out Powell with a short ball. With 10 needed off the final over, Arshdeep nailed a couple of yorkers, but Hetmyer held his nerve to take his team over the line with a couple of sixes.

Sam Curran | PBKS Captain - The wicket was slightly slow, but we didn't start well with the bat and didn't finish well in the end. It was a good effort from the lower order, getting (close) to 150 was excellent, the bowling was good, we kept them down, unfortunately another close loss. We stuck to our plans, bowled and fielded well, but I'm confident we'll bounce back in the next game. Three games is a hard way to fully work out the conditions (at the new venue), but we've adapted well, we won the first match and lost two matches by close margins (by 2 runs and 3 wickets), hard to take, but the boys will be lifted by how well we've played in the last couple of games.

Rovman Powell: Definitely, it’s important for us to get two points, the guys are keeping up, credit to the guys. (On his stand with Hetmyer) The good thing is we both are calm, we talked that we should run fast, we are West Indians, we are boundary-hitters. It’s a challenge but we are professional cricketers. (On being asked about Buttler’s niggle) I think they are doing some very good work with him, I think he would be out for another day or two but it’s good that we have a game in 3-4 days, so he will likely be back by then. I am a good player, if I not getting games then it means the team is doing well. Whenever I get my opportunity, I will give my best.

RR’s run-chase Overs 1-8: 56/0 (RR: 7) Overs 9-14: 34/3 (RR: 5.67) Overs 15-19.5: 62/4 (RR: 10.63) PBKS bowling Rabada and Curran: 4/43 from 8 overs (ER: 5.375) Others: 3/109 from 11.5 overs (ER: 9.21) RR vs PBKS since 2020 Matches: 8 Won by RR: 6 Won by PBKS: 2 Seven of the above matches have been last over finishes.

Sanju Samson | RR captain: (High-catches) We had few funny instances from last year and this year. But I am really happy that everyone is eager to go and catch. I would be very sad if people are just staying away and not catching it. It gets a bit tough actually - the stadium is full of noise and when people call, we are looking at the ball, we can't look who is coming. I need to tell my fast bowlers that it's a bit easier to catch with the gloves instead of hands. We all were (tensed during the run-chase). Games against Punjab in the last 3-4 years, each and every game is very close, very funny feeling. They were bowling really well, it was a funny game. (On Hetmyer) He has been doing it for years and years. Lots of experience, some composure and some confidence about his skills. He was won games many times. Rovman and Hetty - having them was good. Tanush is an interesting youngster. He came in as an allrounder, he had a fabulous Ranji Trophy season with Mumbai and he's been performing well. He's been impressing all the coaching staff and everyone in the nets. We had a proper, settled batting order after the openers, we didn't want to unsettle it and then bring someone up for just one game. Jos is almost ready for the next game, so we just wanted to try him up the order. Very happy to see him (Jaiswal) spend some time in the middle, get those 30s and 40s. That's what this tournament has taught me from last 10 years - never take it for granted. Last game, we did some really great things and we ended up on the losing side. Today, we made a bit more mistakes and we ended up winning the game. It's a very funny game, so we'd like to keep our heads down and just do the process.

Shimron Hetmyer | Player of the Match: (Mindset to finish games) It's just practice, I try as much as possible to bat properly in the nets first and then when everyone's finished, I go back and try my best to hit sixes. It's a blessing and a curse (on being the finisher). Sometimes it happens, sometimes it doesn't. I am happy that I could help the team pull off a victory today. They (pressure) creep in the first couple of balls that I face, afterwards I just try to keep it as clear as possible. Even in the last over after I missed the first two balls, he (Boult) came down to me and he was like "Don't worry, we've got this," and I was able to feed off his energy and it really worked. I would have taken it (single with 2 runs needed off 2 balls). I spoke to Boulty and he said, "I got this." After he said that, I was like even if I don't get the other one, I'll try my best to get a single. Even if we don't win it, at least tie it. I was really looking to get a single or double and then the full toss came and I tried to hit it over the guys that were inside. Being away from family, the only way you could keep yourself up is by just enjoying every moment that you're here.

RR get back to winning ways and are sitting pretty at the top of the table with five wins in six matches. Mind you, they were without Jos Buttler and Ashwin as well today. Not a clinical win but two big positives for them - Jaiswal's 39 at the top and the way Hetmyer finished it off. On the other hand, it was another close agonising final-over loss for Punjab. While Shashank and Ashutosh got them very close in the previous match, their bowlers bowled with a lot of heart to make it an interesting encounter. Well, it's time to bring the curtains down on this contest. Until tomorrow's double-header, it's goodbye from all of us down here.
